        <briefdescription>
<para>\par \b Module Contract\/ \:</para>
<para>\par \b Purpose\/ \:  To normalize pptx-like documents (.ppt, .odp) into the PPTX format via LibreOffice headless conversion, providing a uniform input format for downstream presentation readers. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>\par \b Scope\/ \:  Pptx-like document format normalization via soffice. \par \b Input\/ \:  Files with pptx-like extensions or MIME types. \par \b Output\/ \:  Converted .pptx file path. \par \b Links\/ \:  [USES_API(9): LibreOffice soffice; READS_DATA_FROM(7): <ref refid="namespacededoc_1_1extensions_1aac3b199243c8795f127aefef6c73fa04" kindref="member">dedoc.extensions.converted_extensions</ref>] \par \b Invariants\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>convert() always invokes soffice with <ndash/>headless <ndash/>convert-to pptx.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Output file path is always {dir}/{name_wo_ext}.pptx. \par \b Rationale\/ \:</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>Q: Why soffice instead of python-pptx for conversion? A: soffice handles legacy binary .ppt and .odp formats that python-pptx cannot read. \par \b Changes\/ \:</para>
<para>LAST_CHANGE: [v1.0.0 — Added semantic markup and LDD logging] \par \b Module Map\/ \:</para>
<para>CLASS 9[Converts pptx-like formats to PPTX via LibreOffice] =&gt; PptxConverter \par \b Use Cases\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>[PptxConverter.convert]: User (Upload) → NormalizeToPptx → PptxFileReady </para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
